    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-03-21T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-03-21T13:00:00-05:00" n="13"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d13">
                <head>13. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Austria</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d13fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 440.002/3–2158. Secret. Repeated to Moscow.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Vienna</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1958-03-21T19:00:00+01:00">March 21, 1958, 7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2666. Gruber informed Embassy officer that Chancellor<note n="1" xml:id="d13fn1"
                        >Julius Raab.</note> told Soviet Ambassador whom he had called in on another
                    matter that Austrian Government is giving consideration to idea of joining the
                    Common Market. Gruber said Soviet Ambassador’s reaction was negative but “not
                    too much so.” Chancellor explained that he is not optimistic that the Free Trade
                    Area will come into being, and if it does, it might be so watered down as to be
                    ineffective. The Soviet Ambassador told Chancellor that if he joins the Common
                    Market “those people will have him by the throat.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Matthews</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
